I don't think it's as much of a chemical reaction as it is a thermal one. You'll notice, especially with your matches but also with the candles, as soon as you put the glass on or light the match, there's an eruption of gas from the bottom. Air escaping the glass because the heated up air is escaping through the water but can't push the water out because of the surface tension. That leaves low pressure inside the glass. It's not because the oxygen is being used or transformed, although the transformation is likely happening too, but it is being expelled due to the heat expansion. Then when the air cools down, it is contracting and it can't pull air through the water because of the greater pressure so the water gets pulled in instead. Just a hypothesis but your slow mo seems to really show that rapid air expansion, hence the cork being pushed out.

The statement (at 3:08) of "For every two molecules of oxygen you get on molecule of carbon dioxide" is wrong. Molecular oxygen (as what is in the air) is a diatomic molecule. It is naturally O2 already. So you only need one molecule of O2 (plus a single atom of carbon from somewhere) to make a single molecule of CO2. No net change in the number of molecules of air-based oxygen to carbon dioxide. Unfortunately, the math goes against you for oxygen plus parts of the parifin to water. For every one O2 moledule combining with the hydrogen in the parafin you get two molecules of H2O, so you have a net doubling of molecules. Now, as the gaseous H2O condenses on the inside of the glass, there is one possible way of lowering the volume of gas inside the glass, pulling the water in. (I'm not sure how quickly that happens though.) My suspicion is most of the suction is as a result of the hot gasses (particularly the gasses hot enough to glow in the flame) cooling and trying to reduce in volume to lower the pressure inside the glass which then allows the column of air above the experiment to push the water up into the glass.
